A '''lead''' in [[hydrocarbon exploration]], is a subsurface [[Structural geology|structural]] or [[Stratigraphy|stratigraphic]] feature with the potential to have entrapped [[Petroleum|oil]] or [[natural gas]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Jahn|first=F. |author2=Cook M. |author3=Graham M.|title=Hydrocarbon exploration and production|publisher=Elsevier|year=2008|series=Developments in petroleum science|volume=55|pages=444|isbn= 9780444532367|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ocUT8hEDu1AC&pg=PA24&lpg=PA24&dq=lead+prospect+trap+hydrocarbon+exploration&source=bl&ots=XNeZy4NZkL&sig=Cv9zwN1qZu3h5Fc7i2kf8BoA8-w&hl=en&ei=eFoSS7_-JYax4QaxmqWYBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CDIQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=&f=false|accessdate=2009-11-29}}</ref> When exploring a new area, or when new data becomes available in existing acreage, an explorer will carry out an initial screening to identify possible leads. Further work is then concentrated on the leads with the intention to mature at least some of them into drillable [[Hydrocarbon exploration#Elements of a petroleum prospect|prospects]].

